  "prompt": "What shall I do with a mouse which freezes on the screen and stop responding?",
  "response": "A frozen mouse can be frustrating! Here's a systematic approach to troubleshooting and fixing it:\n\n**1. Basic Checks:**\n\n*   **Give it a moment:** Sometimes, a mouse freezes temporarily due to a spike in system load.  Wait 10-20 seconds to see if it recovers.\n*   **Check the connection (if wired):**\n    *   Make sure the USB or PS/2 cable is securely plugged into the computer.\n    *   Try a different USB port. Some ports might have power issues.\n    *   If possible, test the mouse on another computer to rule out a hardware issue.\n*   **Check the batteries (if wireless):**\n    *   Replace the batteries with fresh ones.  Even if they seem to have some charge, they might be weak.\n    *   Make sure the batteries are installed correctly.\n    *   Look for a power switch on the mouse and make sure it's turned on.\n*   **Check the receiver (if wireless):**\n    *   Ensure the USB receiver is securely plugged into the computer.\n    *   Try a different USB port.\n    *   Move the receiver closer to the mouse (avoid obstructions).\n    *   Try plugging the receiver directly into the computer, avoiding USB hubs (especially unpowered hubs).\n*   **Clean the mouse:**\n    *   If you have an older ball mouse, the ball and rollers inside might be dirty.  Clean them carefully.\n    *   For optical or laser mice, clean the sensor on the bottom with a soft, dry cloth.  A speck of dust can sometimes interfere with tracking.\n*   **Restart the computer:**  This is often the quickest fix for temporary software glitches. If you can't use the mouse, you'll need to use keyboard shortcuts:\n    *   **Windows:** Press the Windows key, use the arrow keys to navigate to the power icon (usually on the bottom-left or right), press Enter, and then use the arrow keys to select \"Restart\" and press Enter again.  Alternatively, you can try Ctrl+Alt+Delete, use the arrow keys to select the power icon, and then restart.\n    *   **macOS:**  Press Ctrl+Command+Eject (or the power button). A dialog box should appear. Use the arrow keys to select \"Restart\" and press Enter.  If that doesn't work, try holding down the power button until the computer shuts down, then press it again to restart.\n\n**2. Identifying the Problem:**\n\n*   **Does the keyboard work?** If the keyboard works, it suggests the problem is specific to the mouse or its driver. If the keyboard *also* doesn't work, it's more likely a system-wide issue, like a frozen operating system.\n*   **Does the mouse light up (if optical/laser)?** If the light on the bottom of the mouse is off, it could indicate a power issue, a broken mouse, or a problem with the USB port.  If it's on but not moving, it's more likely a driver or software issue.\n*   **Did anything change recently?** Did you install new software, drivers, or updates? If so, that might be the cause.\n\n**3. Troubleshooting Steps (If Keyboard Works):**\n\n*   **Device Manager (Windows):**\n    1.  Press the Windows key and type \"Device Manager\". Press Enter.\n    2.  Use the Tab key to navigate through the window.\n    3.  Look for \"Mice and other pointing devices\" and expand it using the right arrow key.\n    4.  Use the down arrow key to select your mouse.\n    5.  Press the Menu key (usually to the right of the spacebar) or Shift+F10 to open the context menu.\n    6.  Try the following, one at a time, testing the mouse after each step:\n        *   **\"Update driver\"**: Select this, and choose \"Search automatically for drivers\".\n        *   **\"Disable device\"**: Select this, confirm, then re-enable it using the same steps.\n        *   **\"Uninstall device\"**: Select this, confirm, and then restart your computer. Windows should automatically reinstall the driver.  If it doesn't, you might need to download the driver from the mouse manufacturer's website.\n    *   Also check for any yellow exclamation marks (!) next to the mouse in Device Manager.  This indicates a problem with the driver.\n\n*   **System Information (Windows):** Check for hardware conflicts.\n    1.  Press the Windows key and type \"System Information\". Press Enter.\n    2.  In the left pane, expand \"Hardware Resources\" and then click \"Conflicts/Sharing.\"\n    3.  Look for any conflicts involving your mouse. If you find one, try updating the driver for the conflicting device.\n\n*   **Check for resource usage:** Open Task Manager (Ctrl+Shift+Esc) and see if any process is using an unusually high amount of CPU or memory.  If so, try closing that process (select it, then click \"End task\").\n\n*   **Safe Mode:** Restart your computer in Safe Mode (how to do this varies depending on your operating system; search online for instructions). Safe Mode loads only essential drivers and services. If the mouse works in Safe Mode, it indicates that a third-party program or driver is causing the problem. You can then try uninstalling recently installed programs or drivers to see if that resolves the issue.\n\n*   **Driver Rollback (Windows):** If you recently updated your mouse driver, try rolling back to the previous version:\n    1.  Open Device Manager (as described above).\n    2.  Locate your mouse under \"Mice and other pointing devices\".\n    3.  Right-click on the mouse and select \"Properties\".\n    4.  Go to the \"Driver\" tab.\n    5.  If the \"Roll Back Driver\" button is available (not grayed out), click it and follow the prompts.\n\n*   **BIOS/UEFI Settings:** In rare cases, mouse issues can be related to settings in your computer's BIOS/UEFI.  You'll need to consult your motherboard's manual for instructions on how to access and navigate the BIOS/UEFI. Look for settings related to USB or pointing devices. Ensure that USB legacy support is enabled if you're using a USB mouse.  **Be very careful when changing BIOS/UEFI settings, as incorrect settings can prevent your computer from starting.**\n\n*   **Check mouse software/utilities:** Do you have any custom software installed for your mouse (e.g., from Logitech, Razer, etc.)? Try updating or uninstalling that software. Sometimes, these utilities can cause conflicts.\n\n**4. Software Issues:**\n\n*   **Scan for malware:**  Run a full scan with a reputable antivirus and anti-malware program.  Malware can sometimes interfere with hardware.\n*   **System File Checker (Windows):** This tool can scan for and repair corrupted system files.\n    1.  Open Command Prompt as administrator (search for \"cmd\", right-click on \"Command Prompt\", and select \"Run as administrator\").\n    2.  Type `sfc /scannow` and press Enter.  Let the scan complete.\n\n**5. Hardware Issues:**\n\n*   **Test with another mouse:** This is the best way to determine if the problem is with the mouse itself or with your computer. If another mouse works fine, your original mouse is likely faulty.\n*   **Inspect the mouse physically:** Look for any signs of damage to the cable (if wired) or to the mouse itself.\n*   **Consider a replacement:** If you've tried all the above steps and the mouse still doesn't work, it's likely a hardware failure, and you'll need to replace the mouse.\n\n**Specific Scenarios and Tips:**\n\n*   **Mouse freezes when playing games:** This could be due to driver conflicts, resource limitations, or game-specific bugs.  Try updating your graphics card drivers and closing unnecessary background programs. Check the game's forums for known issues.\n*   **Mouse freezes intermittently:** This can be harder to diagnose. Pay attention to when the freezes occur (e.g., after a certain amount of time, when using a specific program).  This might give you a clue as to the cause.\n*   **Wireless mouse disconnects frequently:** Try moving the receiver closer to the mouse, changing the channel (if your mouse supports it), or using a different USB port.  Also, check for interference from other wireless devices.\n\n**If all else fails:**\n\n*   **Reinstall the Operating System:** As a last resort, you can try reinstalling your operating system. This will erase all data on your hard drive, so be sure to back up any important files first.  This will rule out any deeply ingrained software issues.\n\nRemember to document the steps you've taken and the results. This will help you narrow down the problem and find a solution. Good luck!\n",
